SIMPLE: turnpike
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turnpike
<hw>Turn"pike`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Turn</ets> +
<ets>pike</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A frame consisting of two bars
crossing each other at right angles and turning on a post or pin, to
hinder the passage of beasts, but admitting a person to pass between the
arms; a turnstile. See <er>Turnstile</er>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I move upon my axle like a <qex>turnpike</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gate or bar set across a road to stop carriages,
animals, and sometimes people, till toll is paid for keeping the road in
repair; a tollgate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A turnpike road.</def> <rj><au>De Foe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A winding stairway.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A beam filled with spikes to
obstruct passage; a cheval-de-frise.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Turnpike man</b></col>, <cd>a man who collects tolls at a
turnpike.</cd> -- <col><b>Turnpike road</b></col>, <cd>a road on which
turnpikes, or tollgates, are established by law, in order to collect
from the users tolls to defray the cost of building, repairing,
etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnpike</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Turnpike
<hw>Turn"pike`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Turnpiked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Turnpiking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To form, as a road,
in the manner of a turnpike road; to throw into a rounded form, as the
path of a road.</def> <rj><au>Knowles.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turnplate</ent>⟦br⟧
